# Railway -> GitOps Migration Pattern

## Applies When
- A real business project must move from Railway to GitOps with database, env, domain, and final cleanup.
- The migration must be proven from runtime evidence, not only from code or config.

## Steps
1. Freeze Railway inventory first: services, domains, env keys, deployments, logs, and whether the source database still exists.
2. Inspect GitOps metadata and runtime separately; do not assume project metadata matches running containers.
3. Treat `DATABASE_URL` as the primary gate. If needed, recover it from a running service through governed tooling and require a read-only row-count probe before releasing.
4. Before creating any new GitOps database runtime, classify the existing runtime first: keep, replace, or accidental duplicate. Do not create speculative replacement clusters.
5. Release GitOps only after env parity and database continuity are verified.
6. If repo-driven auto release is part of the target operating model, confirm both project auto-deploy and configured service watch paths on the GitOps/GitHub integration, then prove them with one real watched-path GitHub push.
7. If the webhook URL is correct but GitHub deliveries show `302`, inspect Cloudflare Access before touching app code. A dedicated path-specific Access application such as `gitops.szlk.ai/webhook/*` with a narrow bypass policy is often required.
8. If the shared build workflow performs service-scoped releases, confirm it can build image-only Compose services that reuse one root Docker image, not only services that declare their own `build:` stanza.
9. Harden webhook ingress after reachability is restored: block non-GitHub source IPs at the Cloudflare edge, rate-limit `gitops.szlk.ai/webhook/*`, and reject replayed deliveries by storing recent delivery receipts.
10. When automating Cloudflare webhook protection, use the `http_request_firewall_custom` ruleset API. Legacy writable `firewall/rules` endpoints may still list rules but can reject all modifications in maintenance mode.
11. Verify on the real production domain, then perform Railway cleanup last.
12. For GitOps cloud-build bundles, keep the runtime Compose file image-based for node rollout. If the build workflow already packages an image tarball, a `build:` stanza in the synchronized Compose file can make the node try to rebuild without the Dockerfile present.
13. Pin the project package manager when using Corepack in Docker builds. Without `packageManager`, Corepack can drift to a newer pnpm release and fail a previously valid lockfile under changed supply-chain policies.
14. Before choosing a host port, inspect same-node business services and pick an unused host port; the GitOps project `target_port` and Compose host port must match.
15. Before the first cutover build, prove the release substrate itself: governed source archive URL, target Agent version, one safe build slot, runner registration when release mode needs it, build memory/disk limits, and a real source download. Application build failures are not actionable until this platform path is known-good.
16. Inventory legacy-platform coupling in both runtime variables and source code. Search for provider URLs, anon/service keys, direct client construction, auth helpers, storage/realtime calls, and server-side content loaders. Classify every hit as data-plane, authentication compatibility, or obsolete; migrating tables alone does not remove provider dependence.
17. Define an identity and session matrix before cutover: provider-native password login, legacy first-login bridge, subsequent login, OAuth login, logout, refresh, protected read/write, admin access, and existing-row updates. Preserve the existing business UUID across identity projection.
18. Keep authentication and database responsibilities explicit. A legacy auth provider may remain temporarily for first-login password verification while all business data moves to GitOps Postgres/PostgREST; do not describe that bounded auth bridge as continued primary-database dependence.
19. For PostgREST compatibility, verify the actual token shape and issuer/secret contract, not only the presence of env keys. Recreate every consumer after secret rotation, then exercise a request that reaches PostgREST; container health and schema-cache startup do not prove JWT acceptance.
20. When overlapping releases exist, monitor each exact deployment id. A newly healthy container may belong to an earlier whole-project release while a later service release is still building; correlate deployment terminal state, Agent report, container creation time, and logs.
21. Add browser-level acceptance after server checks. Require initial navigation state, login/logout state refresh, network request count, public content reads, protected reads/writes, and console/server logs. SSR-disabled account widgets, repeated session initialization, and eager route prefetch can make a same-node migration feel slower even when database latency improved.
22. Export the source successfully before resetting the target schema. Never clear the target as preparation for an export that has not yet produced a readable artifact.

## Evidence
- Validated on BC on 2026-06-17 during a full Railway -> GitOps cutover.
- The migration proved that health checks alone were insufficient because the surviving GitOps database schema had zero rows.
- The migration also proved that a CloudNativePG three-pod database service may be one replicated cluster, while the real duplicate problem is creating a second cluster before the original runtime is classified.
- The migration also proved that `auto_deploy_enabled=true` is insufficient evidence for GitOps repo monitoring; without configured service watch paths, watched GitHub code changes do not auto release.
- The migration also proved that a correct webhook URL can still fail if Cloudflare Access redirects `/webhook/*` to login; `200` delivery proof is the real gate.
- The migration also proved that shared build pipelines need an explicit fallback for image-only services, otherwise webhook-triggered service releases can reach `build_callback` and still fail.
- The migration also proved that "webhook reachable" is not the end state; without edge IP allowlisting, rate limiting, and replay protection, the GitOps ingress remains unnecessarily exposed.
- The migration also proved that Cloudflare's legacy firewall rule write API can fail while the new custom ruleset API succeeds, so future automation should target the ruleset phase directly.
- A standalone GitOps deployment on 2026-07-01 proved three additional build/runtime gates: Corepack pnpm version drift can fail Cloud Build, image bundles require image-based Compose on the node, and host port conflicts must be resolved by matching Compose host port with the GitOps domain `target_port`.
- A 2026-07 production migration validated the added gates: the work required repairing source-archive routing, governed tool exposure, runner/resource protection, PostgREST JWT compatibility, direct legacy-client call sites, concurrent release attribution, and client-side auth rendering before user-visible parity was real.

## Risks
- Do not apply this pattern blindly when the source Railway database is already gone; in that case the task becomes recovery, not straightforward migration.
- Do not let domain cutover or Railway deletion happen before runtime database continuity is proven.
- Do not create a new GitOps database cluster while an older runtime is still present and unclassified; that is how accidental duplicate clusters get created.
- Do not mark the GitOps migration complete until one real watched-path commit proves repo monitoring and automatic release actually work.
- Do not delete or unbind the source platform merely because the target health probe is green. Require data/schema behavior, backup readability, identity/session matrix, browser UX, domain/TLS, and exact source-resource inventory first.
